Problems found
==============

Functional bugs  
1. `findUser` can return `null`/`undefined`, yet the code keeps running and tries to send an e-mail for a non-existing account.  
2. The reset token is never persisted, so the user will never be able to prove ownership of the link that is mailed to him.  
3. No error handling – if `db.findUser`, `sendResetEmail`, or anything else throws, the promise is rejected and Express will crash or return an unhelpful 500.  

Security issues  
1. **Weak / predictable token** – `Math.random()` is not meant for security-sensitive work. Tokens can be bruteforced.  
2. **No token hashing** – if you do store it later, the plaintext should not live in the DB.  
3. **No expiration** – a reset link should be short-lived (e.g. 15-60 min).  
4. **E-mail enumeration** – an attacker can repeatedly POST different addresses and learn which ones exist because `sendResetEmail` is only executed for existing users (timing, SMTP traffic, etc.).  
5. **No rate-limiting / CAPTCHA** – endpoint can be abused for mass e-mailing or password-reset floods.  
6. **Input not validated / sanitised** – a malicious body could be something other than a string or an over-long string, leading to DoS or log injection.  
7. **No CSRF protection** – a JSON API is still CSRF-able with the right content-type; resets should be guarded.  
8. **No HTTPS enforcement** – reset links sent over HTTP are vulnerable to MITM (depends on wider app configuration).  

Suggested fix (example)
-----------------------

```js
const crypto = require('crypto');
const Joi     = require('joi');         // validation lib
const limiter = require('./rateLimit'); // your favourite rate-limiter

app.post('/api/reset-password', limiter, async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    // 1. Validate input
    const { email } = await Joi.object({
      email: Joi.string().email().required()
    }).validateAsync(req.body, { abortEarly: false });

    // 2. Look the user up
    const user = await db.findUserByEmail(email);

    // 3. Always respond the same to avoid enumeration
    if (!user) {
      return res.json({ success: true });
    }

    // 4. Generate a cryptographically secure token
    const rawToken      = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex');
    const hashedToken   = crypto.createHash('sha256').update(rawToken).digest('hex');
    const expiresAt     = new Date(Date.now() + 60 * 60 * 1000); // 1h

    // 5. Persist hashed token + expiry
    await db.savePasswordResetToken(user.id, hashedToken, expiresAt);

    // 6. Send the e-mail (use HTTPS URL)
    await sendResetEmail(user.email, rawToken);

    return res.json({ success: true });
  } catch (err) {
    return next(err); // centralised error handler
  }
});
```

Extra hardening
---------------

• Use a dedicated “password_resets” table with columns: user_id, token_hash, expires_at, consumed.  
• Invalidate any previously issued tokens when a new one is generated.  
• When the user submits the token, hash it again and compare to the stored hash with a constant-time comparison.  
• Delete/mark the token as used after the first successful reset.  
• Enforce HTTPS and include `secure`, `httponly`, `samesite=strict` flags on any session cookies.  
• Consider adding CSRF tokens or requiring the user to supply their current password when logged in.  
• Log resets and alert on unusual frequency per account and per IP.  
• Wrap the route with a captcha after N requests/minute to deter automated abuse.
